#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:20
msgid "|tooltransform|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:22
msgid "The Transform tool lets you quickly transform the current selection or layer. Basic transformation options include resize, rotate and skew. In addition, you have the option to apply advanced transforms such as Perspective, Warp, Cage and Liquid. These are all powerful options and will give you complete control over your selections/layers."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:24
msgid "When you first invoke the tool,  handles will appear at the corners and sides, which you can use to resize your selection or layer. You can perform rotations by moving the mouse above or to the left of the handles and dragging it. You can also click anywhere inside the selection or layer and move it by dragging the mouse."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:26
msgid "You can fine-tune the transform tool parameters using tool options docker. The parameters are split between five tabs: Free Transform, Warp, Perspective, Cage and Liquify."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:30
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Transform_Tool_Options.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:30
msgid "Free Transform docker."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:33
msgid "Free transform"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:35
msgid "This allows you to do basic rotation, resizing, flipping, and even perspective skewing if you hold the :kbd:`Ctrl` key. Holding the :kbd:`Shift` key will maintain your aspect ratio throughout the transform. When you move the center pivot point, pressing :kbd:`Alt` will allow you to limit it to the transformation bounds."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:40
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_free.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:40
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:77
msgid "Free transform in action."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:42
msgid "If you look at the bottom, there are quick buttons for flipping horizontally, vertically and rotating 90 degrees left and right. Furthermore, the button to the left of the anchor point widget allows you to choose whether to always transform using the anchor point, or not."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:44
msgid "`Video of how to use the anchor point for resizing. <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=grzccBVd0O8>`_"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:47
msgid "Rotating the Transformation Bounds"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:49
msgid "It is possible to rotate the visual transformation bounds without transforming the image itself. This is particularly useful when dealing with sections of an image that were drawn diagonally, like for example, a stick at an angle."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:51
msgid "By pressing :kbd:`Ctrl + Alt` before trying to rotate, the cursor will switch to a bounds-rotation cursor, at which point a |mouseleft| + drag will rotate the visual bounds. Then, releasing the keys, a regular transformation can be performed. By rotating the transformation bounds to the actual image being transformed, it can be easier to transform the image afterwards, especially when aligning at a certain angle."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:56
msgid "Perspective"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:58
msgid "While free transform has some perspective options, the perspective transform allows for maximum control. You can drag the corner points, or even the designated vanishing point."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:60
msgid "You can also change the size, shear and position transform while remaining in perspective with the tool-options."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:64
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_perspective.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:64
msgid "Perspective transform."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:69
msgid "Warp allows you to deform the image by dragging from a grid or choosing the dragging points yourself."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:73
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Transform_Tool_Options_Warp.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:73
msgid "Warp Option."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:77
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_warp.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:79
msgid "There are warp options: Rigid, Affine and Similitude. These change the algorithm used to determine the strength of the deformation. The flexibility determines, how strong the effect of moving these points are."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:82
msgid "Anchor Points"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:84
msgid "You can divide these either by subdivision or drawing custom points."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:86
msgid "Subdivision"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:87
msgid "This allows you to subdivide the selected area into a grid."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:89
msgid "Draw"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:89
msgid "Draw the anchor points yourself. Locking the points will put you in transform mode. Unlocking the points back into edit mode."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:94
msgid "Create a cage around an image, and when it's closed, you can use it to deform the image. If you have at least 3 points on the canvas, you can choose to switch between deforming and editing the existing points."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:98
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_cage.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:98
msgid "Transforming a straight banana to be curved with the cage tool."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:101
msgid "Adjust Granularity"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:105
msgid "This adjusts the precision of the cage transform grid. The lower the value, the higher the quality of the transformation (and consequently, the lower the speed). When the granularity is too high, the result starts to look \"blocky\"."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:107
msgid "Preview"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:108
msgid "Adjusts the granularity of the preview. It is recommended to have this higher than the :guilabel:`Real` value, as it speeds up adjusting."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:110
msgid "Real"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:110
msgid "Adjusts the granularity of the final result."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:113
msgid "Hotkeys"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:115
msgid "Both Cage and Warp use little nodes. These nodes can be selected and deselected together by pressing the :kbd:`Ctrl` key before clicking nodes."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:117
msgid "Then you can move them by pressing the cursor inside the bounding box. Rotating is done by pressing and dragging the cursor outside the bounding box and scaling the same, only one presses the :kbd:`Ctrl` key before doing the motion."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:125
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Transform_Tool_Options_Liquify.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:126
msgid "Like our deform brush, the liquify brush allows you to draw the deformations straight on the canvas."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:128
msgid "Move"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:129
msgid "Drag the image along the brush stroke."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:130
msgid "Scale"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:131
msgid "Grow/Shrink the image under the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:132
msgid "Rotate"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:133
msgid "Twirl the image under the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:134
msgid "Offset"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:135
msgid "Shift the image under the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:137
msgid "Undo"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:137
msgid "Erases the actions of other tools."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:141
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_liquefy.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:141
msgid "Liquify used to turn an apple into a pear."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:143
msgid "In the options for each brush there are:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:145
msgid "Mode"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:146
msgid "This is either :guilabel:`Wash` or :guilabel:`Build up`. :guilabel:`Wash` will normalize the effect to be between none, and the amount parameter as maximum. :guilabel:`Build up` will just add on until it's impossible."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:147
msgid "Size"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:148
msgid "The brush size. The button to the right allows you to let it scale with pressure."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:149
msgid "Amount"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:150
msgid "The strength of the brush. The button to the right lets it scale with tablet pressure."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:151
msgid "Flow"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:152
msgid "Only applicable with :guilabel:`Build up`."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:153
msgid "Spacing"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:154
msgid "The spacing of the liquify dabs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:156
msgid "Reverse"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:156
msgid "Reverses the action, so grow becomes shrink, rotate results in clockwise becoming counter-clockwise."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:160
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_deformvsliquefy.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:160
msgid "Liquify on the left and deform brush on the right."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:162
msgid "Krita also has a :ref:`deform_brush_engine` which is much faster than liquify, but has less quality. If you are attempting to make liquify a little faster, note that it speeds up with the less information it needs to process, so working with liquify within a selection or using liquify on a separate layer with little on it will greatly enhance the speed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:171
msgid "The mesh transform is similar to the warp and the cage transform, except that its interface uses patches comprised of Bezier curve segments. This transform mode is particularly useful for placing images and textures on curved surfaces:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:175
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_mesh.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:175
msgid "Curving a logo to an apple with the mesh transform, with the control points shown."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:177
msgid "This is a very keyboard shortcut heavy transform mode. When you start the transform you will see the overlay, which consists of several nodes that can be dragged around. You can drag on the segments between the nodes to curve them precisely, or drag on patches themselves to freely transform them. :kbd:`Ctrl + Alt +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` shortcut on nodes and segments will allow you to subdivide the mesh. For more precision, enable the control points in the tool options, so each Bezier segment can be fine-tuned to your content."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:179
msgid "To assist in maintaining the curvature of a mesh, this tool has a concept of 'locked' transform. This mode is signalled by the lock icon in the cursor, and on by default. When this is enabled, adjusting one segment will also adjust its neighbouring segment in another patch. You can press :kbd:`Shift` key while dragging a segment or control point to turn this feature off, allowing for sharp angles in the mesh. After a sharp angle has been created, the locked mode will try to keep this as well."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:182
msgid "Shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:184
msgid "Node or control point move"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:185
msgid "|mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` any of the round points. The big ones are the 'nodes' which determine the corners of a patch, and the small ones are the 'control points', which determine the curvature for their associated segment."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:186
msgid "Unlocked node or control point move"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:187
msgid ":kbd:`Shift +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on a node or control point."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:188
msgid "Locked segment move:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:189
msgid "|mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on a segment. As explained above, this will adjust neighbouring segments as well, to keep the curvature of the node intact."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:190
msgid "Segment move"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:191
msgid ":kbd:`Shift +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on a segment of the mesh."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:192
msgid "Free patch deform:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:193
msgid "|mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on an empty area inside the mesh. This will allow you to intuitively adjust a segment by just clicking anywhere and dragging. The whole segment will then adjust all its control points around the point of the cursor."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:195
msgid ":kbd:`Ctrl + Alt +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on a border segment to split the mesh"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:196
msgid "Split mesh or Move/Delete split:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:196
msgid ":kbd:`Ctrl + Alt +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on a node to change the split"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:197
msgid ":kbd:`Ctrl + Alt +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` away a node to remove the split"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:198
msgid "Select multiple nodes"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:199
msgid ":kbd:`Ctrl +` |mouseleft| on a node or control or segment, these can then be moved"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:200
msgid "Move selection or mesh"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:201
msgid ":kbd:`Shift +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on empty area outside the mesh."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:202
msgid "Rotate selection or mesh"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:203
msgid "|mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on an empty area outside the mesh, if there is a selection of nodes, it will rotate only them, otherwise the whole mesh will be rotated."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:205
msgid "Scale selection or mesh"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:205
msgid ":kbd:`Ctrl +` |mouseleft| :kbd:`+ drag` on empty area outside the mesh, if there is a selection of nodes, it will scale only them, otherwise the whole mesh will be scaled."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:208
msgid "Tool options"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:209
msgid "Mesh Size"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:210
msgid "Gives precise controls to change the amount of patches vertically and horizontally. When increasing or decreasing the amount of patches, Krita will try to keep the curvature the same, which can be used to your advantage."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:212
msgid "This will toggle the control points."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:213
msgid "Show control points"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:216
msgid "Transform Multiple Layers"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:218
msgid "Krita allows you to transform multiple layers at once."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:220
msgid "In Krita versions older than 5.0 this required using the :guilabel:`Recursive Transform` option while transforming a group layer, whose icon was a little spider. Since 5.0, this option is enabled by default for group layers (To achieve non-recursive transformation you can use the layer lock feature)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:224
msgid "Transforming multiple layers doesn't require a group anymore, now all layers selected in the layer docker will be transformed at once."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:228
msgid ".. image:: /images/tools/Krita_transforms_recursive.png"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:228
msgid "Krita allows you to transforms all the layers in the group, so with this apple, both the lineart as the fill will be transformed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:231
msgid "Continuous Transform"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:233
msgid "If you apply a transformation, and try to start a new one directly afterwards, Krita will attempt to recall the previous transform, so you can continue it. This is a *continuous transform*. You can press the :kbd:`Esc` key to cancel this and start a new transform, or press :guilabel:`Reset` in the tool options while no transform is active."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:236
msgid "Transformation Masks"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../reference_manual/tools/transform.rst:238
msgid "These allow you to make non-destructive transforms, check :ref:`here <transformation_masks>` for more info."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
